    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Seaver on the Trading Block</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By RICHARD SANDOMIR</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Sandomir, Richard</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dolls bearing likeness of former New York Mets pitcher Tom Seaver that was given away at Shea Stadium are being auctioned on eBay (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Not every fan who received a Tom Seaver bobble head doll at Shea Stadium last Sunday apparently cherished the seven-and-a-half-inch-tall ceramic likeness of the Hall of Fame pitcher for long -- or even opened the box.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Not every fan who received a Tom Seaver bobble head doll at Shea Stadium last Sunday apparently cherished the seven-and-a-half-inch-tall ceramic likeness of the Hall of Fame pitcher for long -- or even opened the box.</p>
        <p>Within days, a handful of the squat statuettes, variously described by sellers as ''a magnificent doll'' or a ''rare beauty,'' appeared on eBay to be auctioned, proving how an on-line market can turn a freebie into a commodity.</p>
        <p>RICHARD SANDOMIR</p>
        <p>NO MORE</p>
        <p>BASEBALL: METS NOTEBOOK</p>
      </block>
